# @FunctionalInterface

Java provides an annotation.

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b);

}
```

---

# Why use it?

Suppose your teammate accidentally adds another method.

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b);

    int subtract(int a, int b);

}
```

Compiler immediately gives an error.

Without the annotation, you might not notice until you try to use the interface with a lambda.

---

# Benefits of @FunctionalInterface

✅ Better readability

✅ Compiler validation

✅ Prevents accidental mistakes

---

# Interview Question

### Is `@FunctionalInterface` mandatory?

Answer

No.

It is optional.

Even without it,

```java
interface Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b);

}
```

is still a Functional Interface.

The annotation only tells the compiler to verify that the interface always remains functional.

