# Built-in Functional Interfaces

Instead of creating

```java
interface Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b);

}
```

Java already provides common functional interfaces.

The six most important ones are:

| Interface         | Takes Input | Returns Output | Main Method | Memory Trick                 |
| ----------------- | ----------- | -------------- | ----------- | ---------------------------- |
| Predicate<T>      | 1           | Boolean        | `test()`    | Tests something              |
| Function<T,R>     | 1           | Yes            | `apply()`   | Converts one type to another |
| Consumer<T>       | 1           | No             | `accept()`  | Consumes data                |
| Supplier<T>       | 0           | Yes            | `get()`     | Supplies data                |
| UnaryOperator<T>  | 1           | Same Type      | `apply()`   | Same input and output type   |
| BinaryOperator<T> | 2           | Same Type      | `apply()`   | Two inputs, same output type |

---

# 1. Predicate

### Meaning

Predicate means

```
Check

↓

True or False
```

Always returns

```
boolean
```

---

Syntax

```java
Predicate<Integer> p = n -> n % 2 == 0;
```

Use

```java
System.out.println(p.test(10));
```

Output

```
true
```

---

### Logic

```
10

↓

test()

↓

10 % 2 == 0

↓

true
```

---

Real Project

```
Check User Active?

↓

true

Check Age >18?

↓

true

Check Salary >50000?

↓

true
```

Whenever your answer is **Yes/No**, think **Predicate**.

---

# 2. Function

Function means

```
Take input

↓

Return another value
```

Example

```java
Function<String, Integer> f = str -> str.length();
```

Use

```java
System.out.println(f.apply("Java"));
```

Output

```
4
```

---

Logic

```
Java

↓

length()

↓

4
```

---

Real Project

```
Employee

↓

EmployeeDTO

Customer

↓

CustomerDTO
```

Convert one object into another.

---

# 3. Consumer

Consumer means

```
Accept

↓

Do work

↓

Return Nothing
```

Example

```java
Consumer<String> c = name -> System.out.println(name);
```

Use

```java
c.accept("Sruthi");
```

Output

```
Sruthi
```

---

Notice

No return.

Just action.

---

Real Project

```
Print Log

Save File

Send Email

Display Message
```

---

# 4. Supplier

Supplier means

```
No Input

↓

Produces Output
```

Example

```java
Supplier<String> s = () -> "Welcome";
```

Use

```java
System.out.println(s.get());
```

Output

```
Welcome
```

---

Real Project

```
Generate OTP

↓

Generate UUID

↓

Current Date

↓

Random Password
```

---

# 5. UnaryOperator

Unary

```
One Input

↓

Same Type Output
```

Example

```java
UnaryOperator<Integer> u = n -> n * n;
```

Use

```java
System.out.println(u.apply(5));
```

Output

```
25
```

Input

```
Integer
```

Output

```
Integer
```

Same type.

---

# 6. BinaryOperator

Binary

```
Two Inputs

↓

Same Type Output
```

Example

```java
BinaryOperator<Integer> b = (a, c) -> a + c;
```

Use

```java
System.out.println(b.apply(10, 20));
```

Output

```
30
```

